---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Colophon"
  description="How this site is built and why — living documents with a status and a last-updated date, self-hosted, fast, and almost no JavaScript."
>
  <article class="container section colophon">
    <header class="colophon__header">
      <h1>Colophon</h1>
      <p class="muted colophon__lede">Why this site, and how it works.</p>
    </header>

    <div class="prose colophon__body">
      <p>
        Most personal sites present knowledge as a finished artifact: a polished
        list of papers, a tidy bio, a portfolio frozen at the moment of
        publishing. This one is trying something a little different. It treats
        knowledge as a <strong>process</strong> rather than a product — and it
        tries to make that process visible on the page.
      </p>

      <h2>Living documents</h2>
      <p>
        Every piece of writing here is a living document. Each one carries two
        small markers in its header:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          a <strong>status</strong> — <code>draft</code>, <code>working</code>, or
          <code>stable</code> — that tells you how settled an idea is; and
        </li>
        <li>
          a <strong>last-updated</strong> date, so you can see when I last touched it.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        A <code>draft</code> is a thought still finding its shape. It is reachable
        if you have the link, but it is kept off the public
        <a href="/writing/">Writing</a> list and marked <code>noindex</code>,
        because publishing is not the same as finishing. A <code>working</code>
        document is out in the open but still moving. A <code>stable</code> one is
        settled enough that I would stand behind it today — which is not the same
        as forever.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is deliberate. The convention is borrowed from how I actually work:
        ideas get version numbers, claims come with caveats, and revising in
        public is treated as a feature, not an embarrassment.
      </p>

      <h2>Cross-links and caveats</h2>
      <p>
        Ideas here are meant to connect. Where a claim leans on another note, it
        links to it; where I am unsure, I say so, in the text or in a margin note
        rather than quietly omitting the doubt. Negative results and abandoned
        approaches are worth recording too — the path you did <strong>not</strong>
        take is part of what you learned.
      </p>

      <h2>The design</h2>
      <p>
        The look follows the Swiss International Typographic tradition: a strong
        grid, flush-left text, generous whitespace, large readable type, and a
        single restrained accent. The aim is to get out of the way of the reading.
        The typeface is
        <a href="https://hanken.co/products/hanken-grotesk" rel="noopener"
          >Hanken Grotesk</a
        >, self-hosted; there are no third-party embeds, no tracking scripts, and
        almost no client-side JavaScript. The site is statically built and meant to
        load fast and stay legible for a long time.
      </p>

      <h2>Why &ldquo;knowledge as process&rdquo;</h2>
      <p>
        The deeper reason for all of this is a bet I am still working out: that the
        most valuable part of thinking is often the <em>trace</em> — the
        corrections, the dead ends, the reasons a first attempt was wrong — and not
        just the clean result at the end. A site that hides its revisions throws
        that trace away. This one tries to keep some of it.
      </p>
      <p>
        More to come. Consider everything here a work in progress, in the best
        sense.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>

  <style>
    .colophon {
      max-width: 52rem;
    }
    .colophon__header {
      margin-bottom: var(--space-xl);
    }
    .colophon__lede {
      font-size: var(--step-1);
      margin-top: var(--space-s);
    }
    .colophon__body {
      max-width: var(--measure);
    }
  </style>
</BaseLayout>
